# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-brett
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1941 throughout the world.
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] Any team shown in *italics* indicates a team a player was on from a different league.
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] Any stat from said different league is not calculated to determine the league leader.
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:george-brett/1941-in-baseball-p01] The Negro American League All Star team played against two league teams.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The **1950 major league baseball season** began on April 18, 1950.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 1, with the Philadelphia Phillies and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 47th World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 7.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees swept the Phillies in four games, capturing their 13th championship in franchise history, and their second of five consecutive World Series titles.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The 17th All-Star Game was held on July 11 at Comiskey Park in Chicago, Illinois, home of the Chicago White Sox.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] On Opening Day, April 18, the Boston Braves became the fifth team in MLB to break the color line when they fielded Sam Jethroe.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The only no-hitter of the season was pitched by Vern Bickford on August 9, in the Boston Braves 7–0 victory over the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] This season saw the first use of a bullpen car, by the Cleveland Indians.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The 1950 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 18, featuring all 16 teams, the first time since 1947.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 1, which also saw all 16 teams play, continuing the trend from 1946.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1947 that all 16 teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 7.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] 8 tie games (4 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:george-brett/1950-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 7, with the New York Yankees sweeping the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1950 World Series in four games.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The **1967 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1967 season.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The 64th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League (AL) champion Boston Red Sox and the National League (NL) champion St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] In a rematch of the 1946 World Series, the Cardinals won in seven games for their second championship in four years and their eighth overall.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Series was played from October 4 to 12 at Fenway Park and Busch Memorial Stadium.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] It was the first World Series since 1948 that did not feature the Yankees, Dodgers, or Giants.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] This was the first World Series where the winning team was presented the Commissioner's Trophy.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] As of 2026, this is the last time the Cardinals won the World Series on the road.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] This was the sixth meeting between teams from Boston and St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis for a major professional sports championship.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The "Impossible Dream" Red Sox were led by triple crown winner Carl Yastrzemski (who won the Most Valuable Player award for his 1967 performance) and ace pitcher Jim Lonborg, who won the American League Cy Young Award.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox reached the World Series by emerging victorious from a dramatic four-team pennant race that revitalized interest in the team after eight straight losing seasons.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Going into the last week of the season, the Red Sox, Detroit Tigers, Minnesota Twins, and Chicago White Sox were all within one game of each other in the standings.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The White Sox lost their last five games (two to the lowly Kansas City Athletics and three to the similarly inept Washington Senators) to fall out of the race.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Meanwhile, the Red Sox and Twins met in Boston for the final two games of the season, with Minnesota—who won the AL Pennant two years earlier—holding a one-game lead.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Boston swept the Twins, but needed to wait out the result of the Tigers' doubleheader with the California Angels in Detroit.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] A Detroit sweep would have enabled them to tie the Red Sox for first place.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Tigers won the first game but the Angels won the nightcap, enabling the Red Sox to claim their first pennant since 1946.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Twenty-two-year-old Steve Carlton won 14 games in his first full major league season, beginning what was to be a lengthy and very successful career.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinals overcame the absence of Bob Gibson, who missed almost one-third of the season with a broken leg on July 15 (on disabled list, July 16 – September 6) suffered when he was struck by a ball hit by Pittsburgh's Roberto Clemente.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Gibson still managed to win 13 games, and while he was out, Nelson Briles filled his spot in the rotation brilliantly, winning nine consecutive games as the Cardinals led the N.L. comfortably for most of the season, eventually winning by 10+1⁄2 games over the San Francisco Giants.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Pitching dominated this World Series, with Bob Gibson leading the Cardinals.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Lonborg pitched the decisive final game of the regular season for Boston, so he was unable to start Game 1.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Maris (obtained from the New York Yankees in December 1966) knocked in both of St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis' runs with third and seventh-inning grounders.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Santiago pitched brilliantly and homered in the third inning off Gibson for the Red Sox' only run.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Gibson cemented his reputation as an unhittable postseason pitcher in this series, allowing only three total runs over three complete games.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] His efforts allowed the Cardinals to triumph despite the hitting of Yastrzemski (.500 OBP, .840 SLG), and pitching of Lonborg, who allowed only one run total in his complete-game wins in Games 2 and 5.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] In Game 2, Yastrzemski belted two homers but the story was Lonborg.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Boston ace retired the first 19 Cardinals he faced until he walked Curt Flood with one out in the seventh inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] He had a no-hitter until Julián Javier doubled down the left field line with two out in the eighth.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Lonborg settled for a one-hit shutout in which he faced only 29 batters.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis, the El Birdos (as Cepeda had nicknamed them) took Games 3 and 4, with Briles pitching the home team to a 5–2 victory (a two-run homer by Mike Shannon proved to be the decisive factor), and Gibson tossing a 6–0 whitewashing (with two RBIs apiece by Maris and McCarver).
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] With the Cardinals leading 3 games to 1, Lonborg kept the Bosox in the series with a 3–1 victory in Game 5.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The 25-year-old righthander tossed two-hit shutout ball over 8+2⁄3 innings, then finally gave up a run when Maris homered to right.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Going for the clincher at Fenway Park in Game 6, the visiting team took a 2–1 lead going into the fourth inning when Dick Hughes (who led the National League with a .727 winning percentage and won 16 games during the regular season) gave up a record three homers in a single inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Yastrzemski led off the inning with a long drive over the wall in left center and, two outs later, rookie Reggie Smith and Rico Petrocelli hammered consecutive shots.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Brock tied the game with a two-run homer in the seventh, but Boston responded with four runs of their own in the bottom of that inning and went on for the 8–4 triumph to tie the series at three games all.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinals set a World Series record using eight pitchers.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The decisive Game 7 featured Gibson and Lonborg facing each other for the first time in the series, but Lonborg was starting on only two days' rest and was unable to compete with Gibson, who allowed only three hits over the course of a complete game.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Going into Game 7, both pitchers were 2–0 in the series with Gibson giving up four hits in 18 innings and Lonborg surrendering a single run and four hits in his 18.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Something had to give—and it was Lonborg.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinal ace clearly dominated the finale, allowing only three hits, striking out 10 batters and even adding a home run blast of his own in the fifth.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Javier added a three-run shot off Lonborg in the sixth and Gibson cruised to the decisive 7–2 victory.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] He now boasted a 5–1 record and a 2.00 ERA in two World Series, with 57 strikeouts in 54 innings and only 37 hits allowed.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] In attendance for the opening match-up were Senators Robert F.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Kennedy and Ted Kennedy, both Massachusetts natives and supporters of the Red Sox.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Ace Bob Gibson (13–7, 2.98), who sat out July and August with a broken leg, started Game 1 for the Cardinals while 21-year-old José Santiago (12–4, 3.59) started for the Red Sox.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Santiago, starting because Sox ace Jim Lonborg had pitched the final day of the regular season, won seven straight second-half games helping Boston stave off the Detroit Tigers and Minnesota Twins to win the pennant by one game in a tightly fought race.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Pitching was prime as Gibson and Santiago seemed to have their best stuff for this afternoon game at Fenway.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cards got on the board in the top of the third on a leadoff single to center by Lou Brock, a double by Curt Flood, and a Roger Maris groundout to first scoring Brock from third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Sox came right back to tie the score in the bottom of the same inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After Bob Gibson struck out Red Sox catcher Russ Gibson, Santiago helped his own cause by homering to left center field.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] However, Bob Gibson was masterful the rest of the way finishing with ten strikeouts, allowing just six hits with one walk.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Santiago matched Gibson until the top of the seventh when Brock again led off with a single to right (his fourth hit), promptly stole second base, and eventually scored on back-to-back groundouts by Flood and Maris.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] That run would hold up for a 2–1 Cardinal win, but Lonborg was waiting in the wings to start Game 2.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Jim Lonborg enjoyed his best season as a professional in 1967 capturing the Cy Young Award with an A.L. best 22 wins (against nine losses), was tops with 246 strikeouts, and had an impressive earned run average of 3.16.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Lonborg continued his superb pitching starting Game 2 for the Red Sox and for 7+2⁄3 innings, the Cardinals could only manage one baserunner, a seventh inning walk by Curt Flood.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After Tim McCarver and Mike Shannon led off the eighth with groundouts, Julián Javier turned a Lonborg fastball around, lining a double into the left-field corner breaking up his no-hitter.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Bobby Tolan, pinch-hitting for weak-hitting Dal Maxvill, ended the inning by grounding out to second-base.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Lonborg retired the side in order in the ninth ending the game as close to perfect, giving up just one hit and one walk while striking out four.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The final score was 5–0 to even up the series at one game apiece with an upcoming journey to St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis Cardinals came out of their hitting slumber and tagged Boston starter Gary Bell for three runs on five hits in the first two innings of Game 3.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] A former 16-game winner for the Cleveland Indians, Bell was an early-season pickup who pitched well in 29 games for the Sox going 12–8 with an ERA of 3.16.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] But he didn't have his best stuff against the Cardinals' starter, 23-year-old Nelson Briles.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Briles, after losing 15 games in 1966, alternated between middle-relief and starting pitching in '67, and finished with a neat 14-win, five-loss record (.737 winning percentage—best in the N.L.) and an even neater 2.43 ERA.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The great table-setter Lou Brock started things rolling in the first with a triple to left-center.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Curt Flood followed with a single to center scoring Brock for the game's first run.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] In the second, Tim McCarver led off with a single to center followed by a Mike Shannon home run to left.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Ineffective Gary Bell was pinch-hit for in the third inning, replaced by Gary Waslewski.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Waslewski pitched three perfect innings, striking out three before leaving in the sixth for relief pitcher Lee Stange.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Boston scored their first run in the sixth with Mike Andrews, (pinch-hitting for Bell), singling to center.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Andrews took second on a Tartabull sacrifice, immediately scoring on a Dalton Jones base hit to right.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] But the Cards added some insurance in the bottom of the frame with the disconcerting Brock bunting for a hit, eventually going to third when Stange, attempting a pick-off, threw wild into right-field.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Roger Maris, in his next-to-last season, would have a good Series with ten hits and a home run, scored Brock with a single to right-center.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Briles would finish his complete-game victory with a 1–2–3 ninth, the second out recorded when Reggie Smith would interfere with McCarver who was trying to catch his pop-up foul down the first-base line.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis would send Bob Gibson back to the mound, a championship within reach.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] 54,000 plus fans packed Busch Memorial Stadium in anticipation of yet another Bob Gibson post-season, pitching gem.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis needed was a spark from Lou Brock and this time four runs crossed the plate in the first inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Brock started things rolling with a slow-roller to third—nothing Dalton Jones could do could match Brock's speed, for an infield-hit.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Curt Flood singled to shallow left and Roger Maris powered-up going the other way, doubling into the left-field corner scoring both base-runners.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Orlando Cepeda then flied out, Maris advancing to third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Tim McCarver hit a clutch single to right to score Maris.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After Mike Shannon fouled out to Rico Petrocelli for the second out, Julián Javier would single in the hole between short and third followed by .217 lifetime hitter Dal Maxvill's run-scoring single to left for the Cardinals' fourth run.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] That would be it for Game 1 starter José Santiago who would only last two-thirds of an inning this time out.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Gary Bell would relieve, getting the ninth batter of the inning, Bob Gibson to fly out to left.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Gibson would be on cruise-control the remainder of the game while the Cards would add two more runs off reliever Jerry Stephenson in the third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Cepeda would double into the left-field corner and move to third on a wild pitch.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] McCarver would add a second RBI on a sac-fly to center scoring Cepeda.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Shannon would walk and score on a Julián Javier double just inside the third-base line.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] That would be it for the scoring as Gibson would win his second Series game, a five-hit complete-game that put his Cardinals up, three games to one.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] With their backs up against the wall, manager Dick Williams again put his trust in the dependable Jim Lonborg.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The 25-year-old righty was faced by Steve "Lefty" Carlton.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Carlton was 14–9 in 30 games with a 2.98 ERA, striking out 168 in 193 innings during the regular season.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The game played out very tentatively, with just one early run scored by Boston in the top of the third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After Lonborg struck out leading off the inning, Joe Foy struck a single to left field.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Mike Andrews reached safely at first after a sacrifice attempt was fumbled by Cardinal third-baseman Mike Shannon for an error.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] With two on and one out, team hero Carl Yastrzemski looked at a third strike for the second out, but Ken Harrelson followed with a clutch single to left, scoring Foy.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] This would be enough to saddle Carlton with the loss.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Pitching with a slight cold (and a paper horseshoe in his back pocket) Lonborg again sparkled, at one point retiring 12 straight.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After a Roger Maris single in the fourth, the next batter to reach base was Julián Javier, who got on base in the eighth on an error by Rico Petrocelli.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Carlton was just as good but left after six innings of work and would take the loss despite having no earned runs (the run in the third was unearned).
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] He was replaced by Ray Washburn, who then pitched two scoreless innings.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis Manager Red Schoendienst brought in Ron Willis to pitch the ninth.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox greeted Willis by loading the bases on a George Scott walk, a Reggie Smith double, and an intentional walk to Petrocelli.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Jack Lamabe relieved Willis after a 1–0 count on Elston Howard who promptly popped a single to right scoring Scott.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Maris threw high to the plate, allowing Smith to score the second run.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis came to bat in the last of the ninth in a last attempt comeback bid.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] But Lonborg's luck continued, getting Brock and Flood to ground out to second and third respectively.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Maris spoiled the shutout bid by homering over the right-field fence but Orlando Cepeda ended the game on a ground-out to third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox were now back in the Series, although still down three games to two.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Pivotal Game 6 matched rookie Gary Waslewski (2–2, 3.21) who had only pitched in 12 regular season games, versus one-year wonder Dick Hughes (16–6, 2.67) who pitched three seasons, winning only twice more in 1968 before retiring due to arm problems.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Rico Petrocelli gave the Red Sox an early lead with a second inning blast over the Green Monster in left field.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis came back with two runs in the top of the third when Julián Javier hit a lead-off double off that same Green Monster.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After retiring the next two batters, Waslewski gave up a single to Lou Brock, scoring Javier.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Then after a Brock steal, Curt Flood singled to left, scoring Brock.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] In the Sox half of the fourth, Carl Yastrzemski, Reggie Smith, and Rico Petrocelli would all go deep setting a new World Series record with three home runs in the same inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] A demoralized Hughes wouldn't finish the inning and Ron Willis would be summoned from the bullpen to get the last out, an Elston Howard groundout to third.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Waslewski was very workmanlike, but started to tire in the sixth inning when, after giving up two walks, was replaced by John Wyatt who would get out of the jam retiring Mike Shannon on a popup to short and Javier on a fly to short right.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cards would come back and hit Wyatt hard in the seventh.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After pinch-hitter Bobby Tolan walked, Lou Brock hit a homer into the right-center field bleachers.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Flood and Maris hit long fly-outs to center but their hits stayed in the park to end the inning, St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis had tied the score at four apiece.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox would send ten batters to the plate in the bottom of the seventh inning and regain the lead.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Elston Howard would lead off making both the first and last outs but four runs would cross the plate in-between.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] After all was said and done, the Cardinals would send four pitchers to the mound in the inning and when Hal Woodeshick would come into pitch the eighth, a Series record would be tied with eight (8) pitchers used also setting a two team record of 11 pitchers used.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis had one more good chance to win the game loading the bases in the eighth, but highlighted by a great Yastrzemski catch in left-center, the Cards couldn't push one across and wouldn't score again going quietly in the ninth; with Gary Bell pitching the last two innings for the save.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox survived to play another day and the Series was now tied at three games apiece.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Wyatt took the win and Jack Lamabe, who was the first pitcher for the Cardinals in the eighth, would be given the loss.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The seventh game finally matched up the aces, Bob Gibson against Jim Lonborg.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Lonborg was pitching on two-days rest, while Gibson had rested an extra day since his last outing.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Only once before had a seventh game of a Series brought together starting pitchers who both had 2–0 records in the Series—in 1925, when the Washington Senators' Walter Johnson pitched against the Pittsburgh Pirates' Vic Aldridge.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinals players were angered by the quip "Lonborg and Champagne" which was Dick Williams' response when asked after Game 6 who was to be the Red Sox starting pitcher for the Series-deciding contest and the headline dominating the front page of Boston's *Record American* the morning of Game 7.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] From the start, it was apparent that Lonborg was struggling.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Three Cardinal hits and a wild pitch put St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Two more scored in the fifth on a home run by Gibson, Lou Brock's single and two stolen bases (his seventh steal—a new Series record), and a Roger Maris sacrifice-fly to right.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] A Boston run in the fifth cut the score to 4–1, but the Red Sox dream was abruptly halted in the sixth on a three-run homer by Julián Javier off the arm-weary Lonborg to end his night in the sixth inning.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Gibson allowed only one other Boston run for another complete game, striking out 10.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] With the 7–2 defeat, Boston's "Impossible Dream" ended one win short, and the St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis Cardinals were World Series Champions for the second time in the 1960s, and eighth overall.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The 1967 World Series was the first non-exhibition meeting between Major League Baseball teams from St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis and Boston since the departures of the Boston Braves and St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis Browns following (respectively) the 1952 and 1953 seasons ended regular season meetings between teams from those cities (Braves vs Cardinals, Browns vs Red Sox).
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis-based team defeated a Boston-based team in the championship round of any professional sport until 2019 when the St.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] Louis Blues defeated the Boston Bruins in the 2019 Stanley Cup Final.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] This was the Cardinals' first World Series that was not played in Sportsman's Park, which had closed partway through the 1966 season.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] It was the first of six played in Busch Memorial Stadium, also known as Busch Stadium II, which opened in 1966 to replace Sportsman's Park (which had been renamed Busch Stadium in 1953).
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinals returned to the World Series the next year, where they blew a 3–1 series lead and lost to the Detroit Tigers in seven games after being nine outs away from repeating as champions in Game 5.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Cardinals would win their next championship in 1982 over the Milwaukee Brewers in seven games after being eleven outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox would return to the World Series in 1975, but they lost to the Cincinnati Reds in seven games after being seven outs away from the championship in Game 7.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] They also returned to the World Series in 1986, but lost to the New York Mets, also in seven games after being a strike away from the championship twice in Game 6 and ten outs away from the championship in Game 7.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox and Cardinals would meet again in the 2004 World Series, where the Red Sox swept the Cardinals to break the Curse of the Bambino.
[src:george-brett/1967-world-series] The Red Sox bested them again in six games nine years later.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] The **1971 Major League Baseball draft** took place prior to the 1971 MLB season.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] The draft saw the Chicago White Sox select Danny Goodwin first overall.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] The following are the first round picks in the 1971 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] The June 1971 draft was a productive one, even though none of its top ten choices yielded players who would have memorable major league careers.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] Selected in the regular phase were future Hall of Famers Jim Rice (Boston, 1st round), George Brett (Kansas City, 2nd round) and Mike Schmidt (Philadelphia, 2nd round).
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] Pitcher Mike Flanagan was selected in the 15th round of the June regular phase by Houston, but enrolled at the University of Massachusetts.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] Danny Goodwin, the nation's top pick, could not agree to terms with the White Sox and became the first top choice who did not sign a contract, instead choosing to attend Southern University in Baton Rouge.
[src:george-brett/1971-major-league-baseball-draft] Four years later, Goodwin was again selected first overall, this time by the Angels.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The **1971 National League Championship Series** was a best-of-five series in Major League Baseball’s 1971 postseason that pitted the East Division champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the West Division champion San Francisco Giants.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates won the Series three games to one and won the 1971 World Series against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants did not return to the postseason until 1987.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] This was the third National League Championship Series in all.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] It was the first League Championship Series in either league that was not a sweep for the winning team (Baltimore swept Oakland in the 1971 ALCS).
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] With aces Gaylord Perry and Steve Blass taking the mound for their respective teams, Game 1 looked to be a pitchers' duel.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates struck for two in the top of the third when Dave Cash doubled home Jackie Hernández.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Cash scored the second run when Richie Hebner grounded to Tito Fuentes at second, but Willie McCovey dropped Fuentes' throw when he attempted to field the ball after having to scramble back to first because Perry didn't cover the bag.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants halved the lead in their half of the third when Chris Speier singled, went to second on a Perry sacrifice bunt, and scored on a Ken Henderson single.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Fuentes and McCovey would redeem themselves in the fifth by each slamming two-run homers off Blass for a 5–2 lead.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Al Oliver cut the deficit to 5–4 for the Pirates with two-run single in the seventh, but that was it as Perry went the distance for a complete game win.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] In front of an NBC-TV audience, Pirate first baseman Bob Robertson grew into a star in Game 2.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson smashed three homers, becoming the first to do so in a playoff game.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants struck first in the bottom of the first when Tito Fuentes singled off Dock Ellis and scored on a double by Willie Mays.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] After the Pirates tied the game in the second off John Cumberland when Robertson hit a leadoff double and scored on Manny Sanguillén's single, the Giants retook the lead in the bottom half when Chris Speier hit a leadoff double and scored on Ken Henderson's single.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's first home run of the game tied the score again in the fourth.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Sanguillén's single then knocked Cumberland out of the game.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a stolen base, Jackie Hernández's RBI single off Jim Barr put the Pirates up 3–2.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Gene Clines's home run next inning extended their lead to 4–2.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] A pivotal play occurred just prior to the Pirates' 4-run seventh, when Mays, batting in the bottom of the sixth with two out and his team trailing, 4–2, saw his bid for a bases-clearing double grabbed by right fielder Roberto Clemente.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] After a leadoff double and single, Clemente's RBI single off Don Carrithers made it 5–2 Pirates.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] One out later, Robertsons' three-run home run off Ron Bryant extended their lead to 8–2.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Robertson's third home run in the ninth off of Steve Hamilton made it 9–2.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] A two-run home run from Mays off Bob Miller in the bottom half made it 9–4, but Dave Giusti in relief retired all three batters he faced as the Pirates tied the series heading to Pittsburgh.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Pirates' Bob Johnson and the Giants' Juan Marichal locked into a tight pitcher's duel for eight innings.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Bob Robertson hit a homer in the second, his then-record fourth of the series.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The Giants tied it in the sixth when Ken Henderson singled and scored when third baseman Richie Hebner threw wildly past Robertson at first after fielding a bunt by Tito Fuentes.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Hebner would atone for the error, however, by slamming a game-winning homer in the eighth off Marichal.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Dave Giusti came on in the ninth and saved it for Johnson and the Pirates.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Another anticipated pitching duel between Giants' Gaylord Perry and Pirates' Steve Blass quickly went by the wayside.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Blass lasted only two innings, giving up five runs.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Willie McCovey's RBI single with two on in the first gave the Giants a 1–0 lead, but they left the bases loaded.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] In the bottom half, after a leadoff single and double, Roberto Clemente's two-run single put the Pirates up 2–1, but in the second, Chris Speier's leadoff home run tied the game.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] After two singles and two outs, Willie McCovey's three-run home run put the Giants up 5–2, but the Pirates, however, got Blass off the hook in the bottom of the inning.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Manny Sanguillen singled and 1960 World Series hero Bill Mazeroski, hitting for Blass, also singled.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Richie Hebner then tied the game with a three-run home run.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] The score stayed at 5–5 until the sixth when Dave Cash singled, moved to second on a groundout, and scored on a Roberto Clemente RBI single.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Jerry Johnson relieved Perry and after intentionally walking Willie Stargell, Al Oliver's three-run home run made it 9–5 Pirates.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] Meanwhile, Bruce Kison and Dave Giusti pitched the last seven innings of shutout baseball to close out the series and win the pennant for the first time in 11 years.
[src:george-brett/1971-national-league-championship-series] It is Pittsburgh’s fifth-most recent victory in a postseason series.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] The **1973 Kansas City Royals season** was their fifth in Major League Baseball and first in the new Royals Stadium.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] Promoted from Triple-A Omaha, Jack McKeon replaced the fired Bob Lemon as manager and the Royals finished second in the American League West in 1973 with a record of 88–74, six games behind the Oakland A's.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] The 88 wins were the most in the franchise's brief history, five more than in 1971.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] Lefthander Paul Splittorff (20–11) became the first Royal to win twenty games in a season.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] The Royals opened the new Royals Stadium with a 12–1 rout of the Texas Rangers on April 10.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] The Tuesday night game was attended by 39,464 braving cool temperatures; 39 °F (4 °C) at first pitch.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] On April 27, Steve Busby threw the first no-hitter in Royals history, as visiting KC shut out Detroit 3–0 at Tiger Stadium.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] At Royals Stadium on May 15, Nolan Ryan of the California Angels threw the first no-hitter of his career.
[src:george-brett/1973-kansas-city-royals-season] On August 2, George Brett made his major league debut, starting at third base and hitting a single in a 3–1 road win over the`Chicago White Sox.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The **1973 major league baseball season** began on April 5 while the regular season ended on October 1.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The 44th All-Star Game was held on July 24 at Royals Stadium in Kansas City, Missouri, home of the Kansas City Royals.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The National League won, 7–1, and was the second win in what would be a 10-win streak that lasted until 1983.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the designated hitter rule in the American League.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] American League umpires began wearing burgundy blazers with blue pants, a change from the navy blue coats and gray pants worn the previous five seasons (1968–1972).
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The burgundy blazers were worn through 1979.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] A lockout in the offseason (February 8–25) did not result in any regular season games being canceled, but the start of spring training was delayed.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The 1973 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 12 teams.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] Each league was split into two six-team divisions.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against their five division rivals, totaling 90 games, and 12 games against six interdivision opponents, totaling 72 games.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1969 and would be used until 1977 in the American League and 1993 in the National League.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 5, featuring a game between the Cincinnati Reds and Houston Astros, while National League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring eight teams.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] In a scheduling oddity, April 30 saw all teams not play, the last time all teams would be off (aside from All-Star breaks and labor shortages) until June 29, 1998.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on September 30, featuring 10 teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring four teams.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The National League Championship Series took place between October 6 and October 10, while the American League Championship Series took place between October 6 and October 11.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 13 and October 21.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] 1 tie game (0 in AL, 1 in NL), which is not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and was replayed again) occurred during the season.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 6 and ended on October 21 with the Oakland Athletics defeating the New York Mets in the 1973 World Series in seven games.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Royals leave Municipal Stadium from which they played four seasons and opened Royals Stadium, where they continue to play to the present day.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees would play their final game at Yankee Stadium on September 30, in what would be a two year hiatus caused by renovations.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at Shea Stadium, the home of their cross-town rival New York Mets, before returning to a newly renovated Yankee Stadium in 1976.
[src:george-brett/1973-major-league-baseball-season] NBC was the exclusive national TV broadcaster of MLB, airing the weekend *Game of the Week*, *Monday Night Baseball*, the All-Star Game, both League Championship Series, and the World Series.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett's 3,154 career hits are second most by any third baseman in major league history (after only Adrian Beltré's 3,166) and rank 18th all-time.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He is one of five players in MLB history to accumulate 3,000 hits, 300 home runs, and a career .300 batting average (the others being Hank Aaron, Willie Mays, Miguel Cabrera, and Stan Musial).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1999 in his first year of eligibility, and is the only player in MLB history to win a batting title in three different decades.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was also a member of the Royals' 1985 World Series victory over the St.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was named the Royals' interim hitting coach in 2013 on May 30, but he stepped down from the position on July 25 to resume his position of vice president of baseball operations.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 2015, he won his second World Series ring when the Royals won the series in 5 games over the New York Mets.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was born in Glen Dale, West Virginia, the youngest of four sons of a sports-minded family.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Ken, the second oldest, became a major league pitcher who pitched in the 1967 World Series at age 19.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brothers John (eldest) and Bobby had brief careers in the minor leagues.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] All of George's brothers were born in Brooklyn.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Jack and Ethel Brett then moved the family from the Northern Panhandle of West Virginia to the Midwest, and three years later to El Segundo, California, a suburb of Los Angeles, just south of Los Angeles International Airport.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] George grew up hoping to follow in the footsteps of his older brothers.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He graduated from El Segundo High School in 1971 and was selected by the Kansas City Royals in the second round (29th overall) of the 1971 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was high school teammates with pitcher Scott McGregor.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett began his professional baseball career as a shortstop, but had trouble going to his right defensively and was soon shifted to third base.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] As a third baseman, his powerful arm remained an asset, and he remained at that spot for more than 15 years.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett's minor league stops were with the Billings Mustangs for the Rookie-level Pioneer League in 1971, the San Jose Bees of the Class A California League in 1972, and the Omaha Royals of the Class AAA American Association in 1973, batting .291, .274, and .284, respectively.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The Royals promoted Brett to the major leagues on August 2, 1973.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He made his major league debut that day against the Chicago White Sox, going 1-for-4 as the starting third baseman.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett won the starting third base job in 1974 (replacing Paul Schaal), but struggled at the plate until he asked for help from Charley Lau, the Royals' batting coach.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Spending the All-Star break working together, Lau taught Brett how to protect the entire plate and cover up some holes in his swing that experienced big-league pitchers were exploiting.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Armed with this knowledge, Brett developed rapidly as a hitter, and finished the year with a .282 batting average, two home runs and 47 RBI in 113 games.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett topped the .300 mark for the first time in 1975, hitting .308 with 11 home runs and 90 RBI in 159 games.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He finished the season leading the league in hits (195) and triples (13).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He then won his first batting title in 1976 with a .333 average, seven home runs and 67 RBI in 159 games.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The four contenders for the batting title that year were Brett and Royals teammate Hal McRae, and Minnesota Twins teammates Rod Carew and Lyman Bostock.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In dramatic fashion, Brett went 2-for-4 in the final game of the season against the Twins, beating out his three rivals, all playing in the same game.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His lead over second-place McRae was less than .001.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett won the title when a fly ball dropped in front of Twins left fielder Steve Brye, bounced on the Royals Stadium AstroTurf and over Brye's head to the wall; Brett circled the bases for an inside-the-park home run.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] McRae, batting just behind Brett in the line up, grounded out and Brett won his first batting title.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] From May 8 through May 13, 1976, Brett had three or more hits in six consecutive games, a major league record.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] A month later, he was on the cover of *Sports Illustrated* for a feature article, and made his first of 13 All-Star teams.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The Royals won the first of three straight American League West Division titles, beginning a great rivalry with the New York Yankees—whom they faced in the American League Championship Series each of those three years.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In the fifth and final game of the 1976 ALCS, Brett hit a three-run homer in the top of the eighth inning to tie the score at six—only to see the Yankees' Chris Chambliss launch a solo shot in the bottom of the ninth to give the Yankees a 7–6 win.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett finished second in American League MVP voting to Thurman Munson.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] A year later, Brett emerged as a power hitter, batting .312 while clubbing 22 home runs and recording 88 RBI in 139 games, as the Royals headed to another ALCS.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In Game 5 of the 1977 ALCS, following an RBI triple, Brett slid into third and was called safe then was kicked in the head by Graig Nettles, after which Brett stood and threw a punch at Nettles, igniting a bench-clearing brawl.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1978, Brett batted .294 (the only time between 1976 and 1983 in which he did not bat at least .300) with nine home runs and 62 RBI in 128 games, helping the Royals win a third consecutive AL West title.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] However, Kansas City once again lost to the Yankees in the ALCS, but not before Brett hit three home runs off Catfish Hunter in Game 3, becoming the second player to hit three home runs in an LCS game (Bob Robertson was the first, having done so in Game 2 of the 1971 NLCS).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett followed with a successful 1979 season, in which he finished third in AL MVP voting.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He became the sixth player in league history to have at least 20 doubles, triples and homers all in one season (42–20–23) and led the league in hits (212) and triples (20) while batting .329, with an on-base percentage of .376 and a slugging percentage of .563.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] All these impressive statistics were just a prelude to 1980, when Brett won the American League MVP and batted .390, a modern record for a third baseman.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was also named *The Sporting News* Sportsman of the Year.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett's batting average was at or above .400 as late in the season as September 19, and the country closely followed his quest to bat .400 for an entire season, a feat which has not been accomplished since Ted Williams in 1941.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett's 1980 batting average of .390 is second only to Tony Gwynn's 1994 average of .394 (Gwynn played in 110 games and had 419 at-bats in the strike-shortened season, compared to Brett's 449 at bats in 1980) for the highest single season batting average since 1941.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett also recorded 118 runs batted in, while appearing in just 117 games; it was the first instance of a player averaging one RBI per game (in more than 100 games) since Walt Dropo thirty seasons prior.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He led the American League in both slugging and on-base percentage.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett started out slowly, hitting only .259 in April.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In May, he hit .329 to get his season average to .301.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In June, the 27-year-old third baseman hit .472 (17-for-36) to raise his season average to .337, but played his last game for a month on June 10, not returning to the lineup until after the All-Star Break on July 10 due to him tearing a ligament in his foot while trying to steal second.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In July, after being off for a month, he played in 21 games and hit .494 (42-for-85), raising his season average to .390.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett started a 30-game hitting streak on July 18, which lasted until he went 0-for-3 on August 19 (the following night he went 3-for-3).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His high mark for the season came a week later, when Brett's batting average was at .407 on August 26, after he went 5-for-5 on a Tuesday night in Milwaukee.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He batted .430 for the month of August (30 games), and his season average was at .403 with five weeks to go.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] For the three hot months of June, July, and August 1980, Brett played in 60 American League games and hit .459 (111-for-242), most of it after a return from a monthlong injury.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] For these 60 games, he had 14 home runs and 69 RBI.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett missed another 10 days in early September and hit just .290 for the month.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His average was at .400 as late as September 19, but he then had a 4-for-27 slump, and the average dipped to .384 on September 27, with a week to play.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] For the final week, Brett went 10-for-19, which included going 2-for-4 in the final regular season game on October 4.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His season average ended up at .390 (175 hits in 449 at-bats = .389755), and he averaged more than one RBI per game.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett led the league in both on-base percentage (.454) and slugging percentage (.664) on his way to capturing 17 of 28 possible first-place votes in the MVP race.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Since Al Simmons also batted .390 in 1931 for the Philadelphia Athletics, the only higher averages subsequent to 1931 were by Ted Williams of the Red Sox (.406 in 1941) and Tony Gwynn of the San Diego Padres (.394 in the strike-shortened 1994 season).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] More importantly, the Royals won the American League West, and would face the AL East champion New York Yankees in the ALCS.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] During the 1980 post-season, Brett led the Royals to their first American League pennant, sweeping the playoffs in three games from the rival Yankees who had beaten K.C. in the 1976, 1977 and 1978 playoffs.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] During Game 2 of the 1980 ALCS, Willie Randolph was on first base in the top of the eighth with two outs and the Royals up by just one run.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Bob Watson hit a ball to the left field corner of Royals Stadium.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The ball bounced right to Willie Wilson, but Wilson was not known for having a great arm, and third base coach Mike Ferraro waved Randolph home.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Wilson overthrew U L Washington, the cut-off man, but Brett was in position behind him to catch the ball, then throw to Darrell Porter, who tagged out Randolph in a slide.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] TV cameras captured a furious George Steinbrenner fuming immediately after the play.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett claimed after the game that he had deliberately positioned himself to cut off the throw in case Washington missed it, but Tommy John of the Yankees disagreed, thinking that if Brett had been backing up Washington, he would have been between shortstop and home plate, not over behind third base.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Either way, he was in the perfect position to throw out Randolph.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In Game 3, Brett hit a ball well into the third deck of Yankee Stadium off Yankees closer Goose Gossage.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Gossage's previous pitch had been timed at 97 mph, leading ABC broadcaster Jim Palmer to say, "I doubt if he threw that ball 97 miles an hour." A moment later Palmer was given the actual reading of 98.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] "Well, I said it wasn't 97", Palmer replied.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett then hit .375 in the 1980 World Series, but the Royals lost in six games to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] During the Series, Brett made headlines after leaving Game 2 in the sixth inning due to hemorrhoid pain.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett had minor surgery the next day, and in Game 3 returned to hit a home run as the Royals won in 10 innings 4–3.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] After the game, Brett was famously quoted "...my problems are all behind me".
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1981, he missed two weeks of spring training to have his hemorrhoids removed.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] On May 14, 1981, Brett hit UPI photographer Tom Gralish in the head with a crutch while Gralish was photographing him after a loss at Royals Stadium.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Roughly two weeks later, in a fit of anger, he destroyed two toilets and a sink at Metropolitan Stadium as reported by sportswriter Mike Fish.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] On September 15 at a hotel in Anaheim, Brett confronted Fish about his reporting.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett pushed reporter Janis Carr and had to be restrained by teammates Willie Wilson and Greg Keatley.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Police were called but no arrests were made.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] On July 24, 1983, in a game against the Yankees at Yankee Stadium, Brett hit a two-run homer off Goose Gossage in the top of the ninth inning with two out to put the Royals up 5–4.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] After the home run, Yankees manager Billy Martin cited to the umpires a rule stating that any foreign substance on a bat could extend no further than 18 inches from the knob.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The umpires measured the amount of pine tar, a legal substance used by hitters to improve their grip, on Brett's bat.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The pine tar extended about 24 inches, leading home plate umpire Tim McClelland to signal Brett out and end the game as a Yankees win.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] An enraged Brett charged out of the dugout directly toward McClelland, forcing the two umpires and Royals manager Dick Howser to physically restrain him.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The Royals quickly issued a challenge to the outcome.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] It was upheld by American League president Lee MacPhail, who ruled that while the bat should have been excluded from future use, the home run should not have been nullified.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Amid much controversy, the game was resumed on August 18, 1983, from the point of Brett's home run and ended with a Royals win.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1985, Brett had another brilliant season in which he helped propel the Royals to their second American League Championship.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He batted .335 with 30 home runs and 112 RBI in 155 games, finishing in the top 10 of the league in 10 different offensive categories.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Defensively, he won his only Gold Glove, which broke Buddy Bell's six-year run of the award, and finished second in American League MVP voting to Don Mattingly.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In the final week of the regular season, he went 9-for-20 at the plate with seven runs, five homers, and 9 RBI in six crucial games, five of them victories, as the Royals closed the gap and won the division title at the end.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was MVP of the 1985 playoffs against the Toronto Blue Jays, with an incredible Game 3.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] With KC down in the series two games to none, Brett went 4-for-4, homering in his first two at bats against Doyle Alexander, and doubled to the same spot in right field in his third at bat, leading the Royals' comeback.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett then batted .370 in the World Series against the St.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Louis Cardinals, including a four-hit performance in Game 7.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The Royals again rallied from a 3–1 deficit to become World Series champions for the first time in their history.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1988, Brett moved across the diamond to first base in an effort to reduce his chances of injury and had another top-notch season with a .306 average, 24 home runs and 103 RBI in 157 games.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] But after batting just .282 with 12 homers and 80 RBI in 124 games the next year, it looked like his career might be slowing down.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He got off to a terrible start in 1990 and at one point even considered retirement.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] But his manager, former teammate John Wathan, encouraged him to stick it out.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Finally, in July, the slump ended and Brett batted .386 for the rest of the season.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In September, he caught Rickey Henderson for the league lead, and in a battle down to the last day of the season, captured his third batting title with a .329 mark.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] This feat made Brett the only major league player to win batting titles in three different decades.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett played three more seasons for the Royals, mostly as their designated hitter, but occasionally filling in for injured teammates at first base.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He passed the 3,000-hit mark in 1992, though he was picked off by Angels first baseman Gary Gaetti after stepping off the base to start enjoying the moment.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett retired after the 1993 season; in his final at-bat, he hit a single up the middle against Rangers closer Tom Henke and scored on a home run by now teammate Gaetti.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His last game was also notable as being the final game ever played at Arlington Stadium.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1999, with what was then the fourth-highest voting percentage in baseball history (98.2%), trailing only Tom Seaver, Nolan Ryan, and Ty Cobb.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] His voting percentage was higher than all-time greats Babe Ruth, Hank Aaron, Willie Mays, Stan Musial, Ted Williams, and Joe DiMaggio.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 2007, Cal Ripken Jr. passed Brett with 98.5% of the vote.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] 5 was retired by the Royals on May 14, 1994, only the second in Royals history, after former Royals manager, Dick Howser's No.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was selected the Hometown Hero for the Royals in a two-month fan vote revealed in an hour-long telecast on ESPN on September 27, 2006.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was one of the few players to receive more than 400,000 votes.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett's 3,154 career hits are the second most by a third baseman in major league history, surpassed only by Adrián Beltré (3,166 hits), and 18th among all players.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Baseball historian Bill James regards him as the second-best third baseman of all time, trailing only his contemporary, Mike Schmidt.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1999, he ranked Number 55 on *The Sporting News'* list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was nominated as a finalist for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett is one of only five players in MLB history—the other four being Stan Musial, Willie Mays, Miguel Cabrera, and Hank Aaron—to accumulate 3,000 hits, 300 home runs, and a career .300 batting average.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Most indicative of his hitting style, Brett is seventh on the career doubles list with 665, trailing only Tris Speaker, Pete Rose, Stan Musial, Ty Cobb, Albert Pujols and Craig Biggio).
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was a highly effective hitter in the postseason.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] A photo in the July 1976 edition of *National Geographic* showing Brett signing baseballs for fans with his team's name emblazoned across his shirt was the inspiration for New Zealand singer-songwriter Lorde's 2013 song "Royals," which won the 2014 Grammy Award for Song of the Year.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was inducted into the Missouri Sports Hall of Fame in 1994.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett was inducted into the Kansas Sports Hall of Fame in 2017.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett is credited with popularizing the phrase the Mendoza Line, which is used to represent a sub-.200 batting average, historically regarded as unacceptable at the Major League level.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] It derives from shortstop Mario Mendoza, a career .215 hitter who finished below .200 five times in his nine seasons in the big leagues—including .198 the year the term is claimed to have been coined by a pair of his teammates in Tom Paciorek and Bruce Bochte in 1979.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett referred to the Mendoza Line in an interview, which was picked up by ESPN baseball anchor Chris Berman and then expanded into the world of *SportsCenter*.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Following his playing career Brett became a vice president of the Royals, and has worked as a part-time coach, as a special instructor in spring training, as an interim batting coach, and as a roving instructor helping minor league prospects develop.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He also runs a baseball equipment and glove company named Brett Bros. with brothers Bobby, and, until his death in 2003, Ken.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He has also lent his name to a restaurant on the Country Club Plaza in Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1998, Brett worked as a color analyst on regional *Fox Saturday Baseball* telecasts.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett has continued to raise money for amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), commonly known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett started to raise money for the Keith Worthington Chapter during his playing career in the mid-1980s.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett and his dog Charlie appeared in a PETA ad campaign, encouraging people not to leave their canine companions in the car during hot weather.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He also threw out the ceremonial first pitch to Mike Napoli at the 2012 Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] On May 30, 2013, the Royals announced that Brett and Pedro Grifol would serve as batting coaches for the organization.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] On July 25, 2013 (the day following the 30th anniversary of the pine tar incident), the Royals announced that Brett would serve as vice president of baseball operations.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 2015, Brett was the National Baseball Hall of Fame recipient of the Bob Feller Act of Valor Award for his support of current and former service members of the United States Military.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett appeared as himself in the ABC sitcom *Modern Family* on March 28, 2018, alongside main cast member Eric Stonestreet, a Kansas City native and Royals fan, whose character on the show is also an avid fan.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett appeared as himself in the *Brockmire* episode "Player to Be Named Later", in which he is dating Jules (Amanda Peet), much to Brockmire's despair; in the episode "Low and Away", Jules informs Brockmire that she and her now-husband Brett are getting a divorce.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He was a recurring guest on the podcast *Pardon My Take* which is presented by Barstool Sports and hosted by Dan "Big Cat" Katz and PFT Commenter.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1998, an investor group headed by Brett and his older brother, Bobby, made an unsuccessful bid to purchase the Kansas City Royals.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] Brett is the principal owner of the Tri-City Dust Devils, the Single-A affiliate of the Los Angeles Angels.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] He and his brother Bobby also co-own the Rancho Cucamonga Quakes, a Los Angeles Dodgers Single-A partner, and lead ownership groups that control the Spokane Chiefs of the Western Hockey League, and the West Coast League's Bellingham Bells.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] In 1992, Brett married the former Leslie Davenport, and they reside in the Kansas City suburb of Mission Hills, Kansas.
[src:george-brett/george-brett] The couple has three sons: Jackson, Dylan, and Robin.
